ale of a Tale''\n|}\n\n===Video games===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size: 88%\"\n|-\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! Year !! Title !! Role\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 1995 || ''[[Disney's Animated Storybook|Disney's Animated Storybook: Winnie the Pooh and the Honey Tree]]'' || Kanga\n|-\n| ''[[Battle Beast (video game)|Battle Beast]]'' || rowspan=\"3\" | Additional voices\n|-\n| 1996 || ''[[Arcade America]]''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" | 1997 || ''[[Castlevania: Symphony of the Night]]''\n|-\n| ''Ready for Math with Pooh'' || rowspan=\"2\" | Kanga\n|-\n| ''[[Ready to Read with Pooh]]''\n|-\n| ''[[Herc's Adventures]]'' || [[Hera]]\n|}\n\n===Theme park attraction===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size: 88%\"\n|-\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! Year !! Title !! Role !! Notes\n|-\n| 1982 || ''[[The American Adventure (Epcot)|The American Adventure]]'' || Jane || [[Epcot|EPCOT]] attraction, [[Walt Disney World]]\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|id=0663506|name=Patricia Parris}}\n* [http://www.behindthevoiceactors.com/Pat-Parris/ Patricia Parris] at Behind The Voice Actors\n* [http://voicechasers.com/database/showactor.php?actorid=1041 Patricia Parris] at Voice Chasers\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Parris, Patricia}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American voice actresses]]\n[[Category:American radio actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:American video game actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Ohio]]\n[[Category:People from Hamilton, Ohio]]\n[[Category:Brenau University alumni]]\n[[Category:Hanna-Barbera people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n", "name_user": "Moe1810", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTelevision (animated)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Patricia_Parris"}
{"title_page": "Paul Smith (artist)", "text_new": "{{other people|Paul Smith}}\n\n  <!-- The Infobox_Biography entries are examples only\n{{Infobox Person\n| name   = Socrates(example)\n| image     = socrates.png\n| image_size     = 180px\n| caption  = The Ancient Greek philosopher\n| birth_date  = [[1925]]\n| birth_place = \n| death_date  = [[2007]]\n| death_place = \n| occupation     = [[Artist]]\n| spouse         = None\n| parents        =\n| children       = None\n}}-->\n\n'''Paul Smith''' (September 21, 1921 &ndash; June 25, 2007) was an American typewriter artist.\n<!--<ref>Last, first (date).  [http://URL Name of page].  Page xx.  Publisher: xxxx</ref>-->\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Early life===\n<!--[[Image:Subject's earliest portrait.ext|thumb|right|Photo caption]]-->\nSmith was born in 1921 in [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]]. He suffered from severe [[spastic cerebral palsy]] from an early age. It took Smith 16 years to learn how to talk, and double that to learn to talk [THIS MAKES NO SENSE]. [STRIKE ALL AFTER \"talk,\"] The loss of fine motor control of his face and hands made it impossible for him to attend school\u2014or even eat, clothe, or bathe himself\u2014and also made it difficult for him to express himself. <!--<ref>Mitch, Jim (2002).  [http://www.paulsmithfoundation.org/main_biography.html].</ref>-->\n\nEarly in life Paul discovered the typewriter and a technique for using it to create pictures. He was able to use one hand to steady the other and thus press the desired key. He was creating typewriter art by the age of 15 and steadily refined his technique.\n\nIn the 1940s, Paul's family moved to [[Hollywood, Florida]].\n\nPaul never married and had no children. In 1967 he entered the retirement facility Rose Haven in Roseburg Oregon.\n\n===Death and afterward===\nAs he aged, Smith's cataracts worsened, and he was not able to create art of as high a quality. He stopped creating pictures in 2004.\n\nSmith died in June 2007.\n\n==Philosophical and/or political views==\nHe was devoted to his family and was a committed Catholic.\n\n==Published works==\nPaul did not publish any works, but his work has been collected into several books of art.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Typewriter]]\n*[[ASCII art]]\n\n==References==\n{{no footnotes|date=March 2009}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*https://web.archive.org/web/20071020155210/http://oregonnews.com/article/20070628/NEWS/70628031/ Obituary and more information\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=svzPm8lT36o Typewriter Artist] - 2004 [[KING-TV]] story\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Smith, Paul}}\n[[Category:1921 births]]\n[[Category:2007 deaths]]\n\n\n{{US-artist-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{other people|Paul Smith}}\n\n  <!-- The Infobox_Biography entries are examples only\n{{Infobox Person\n| name   = Socrates(example)\n| image     = socrates.png\n| image_size     = 180px\n| caption  = The Ancient Greek philosopher\n| birth_date  = [[1925]]\n| birth_place = \n| death_date  = [[2007]]\n| death_place = \n| occupation     = [[Artist]]\n| spouse         = None\n| parents        =\n| children       = None\n}}-->\n\n'''Paul Smith''' (September 21, 1921 &ndash; June 25, 2007) was an American typewriter artist.\n<!--<ref>Last, first (date).  [http://URL Name of page].  Page xx.  Publisher: xxxx</ref>-->\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Early life===\n<!--[[Image:Subject's earliest portrait.ext|thumb|right|Photo caption]]-->\nSmith was born in 1921 in [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]]. He suffered from severe [[spastic cerebral palsy]] from an early age. It took Smith 16 years to learn how to talk, and double that to learn to talk. The loss of fine motor control of his face and hands made it impossible for him to attend school\u2014or even eat, clothe, or bathe himself\u2014and also made it difficult for him to express himself. <!--<ref>Mitch, Jim (2002).  [http://www.paulsmithfoundation.org/main_biography.html].</ref>-->\n\nEarly in life Paul discovered the typewriter and a technique for using it to create pictures. He was able to use one hand to steady the other and thus press the desired key. He was creating typewriter art by the age of 15 and steadily refined his technique.\n\nIn the 1940s, Paul's family moved to [[Hollywood, Florida]].\n\nPaul never married and had no children. In 1967 he entered the retirement facility Rose Haven in Roseburg Oregon.\n\n===Death and afterward===\nAs he aged, Smith's cataracts worsened, and he was not able to create art of as high a quality. He stopped creating pictures in 2004.\n\nSmith died in June 2007.\n\n==Philosophical and/or political views==\nHe was devoted to his family and was a committed Catholic.\n\n==Published works==\nPaul did not publish any works, but his work has been collected into several books of art.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Typewriter]]\n*[[ASCII art]]\n\n==References==\n{{no footnotes|date=March 2009}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*https://web.archive.org/web/20071020155210/http://oregonnews.com/article/20070628/NEWS/70628031/ Obituary and more information\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=svzPm8lT36o Typewriter Artist] - 2004 [[KING-TV]] story\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Smith, Paul}}\n[[Category:1921 births]]\n[[Category:2007 deaths]]\n\n\n{{US-artist-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Frankt3095", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly life:Edit is to clarify the sentence.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Smith_(artist)"}
