{"title_page": "1934 United States Senate election in New Jersey", "text_new": "{{Infobox Election\n| election_name = 1934 United States Senate election in New Jersey\n| country = New Jersey\n| flag_year = 1908\n| type = presidential\n| ongoing = no\n| previous_election = 1928 United States Senate election in New Jersey\n| previous_year = 1928\n| next_election = 1938 United States Senate special election in New Jersey\n| next_year = 1938 (special)\n| election_date = November 6, 1934\n| image1 = [[File:Arthur Harry Moore circa 1926.png|x150px]]\n| nominee1 = '''[[A. Harry Moore]]'''\n| party1 = Democratic Party (United States)\n| popular_vote1 = '''785,971'''\n| percentage1 = '''57.90%'''\n| image2 = [[File:Hamiltonkean.jpg|x150px]]\n| nominee2 = [[Hamilton F. Kean]]\n| party2 = Republican Party (United States)\n| popular_vote2 = 554,483\n| percentage2 = 40.85%\n| title = Senator\n| before_election = [[Hamilton F. Kean]]\n| before_party = Republican Party (United States)\n| after_election = [[A. Harry Moore]]\n| after_party = Democratic Party (United States)\n}}\n{{ElectionsNJ}}\nThe '''United States Senate election of 1934 in New Jersey''' was held on November 6, 1934. \n\nIncumbent [[Republican Party (US)|Republican]] Senator [[Hamilton F. Kean]] ran for re-election to a second term in office, but was defeated by Governor of New Jersey [[A. Harry Moore]] in a landslide. \n\nThis was among the nine seats Democrats gained in this year's elections. \n\nThis election also marks the end of a streak of four straight elections in which the incumbents were defeated, beginning in 1916.\n\n==Candidates==\n*John C. Butterworth (Socialist Labor)\n*William L. Detmering (Independent Voters)\n*Rebecca Grecht (Communist)\n*Elwood Hollingsworth (Prohibition)\n*[[Hamilton F. Kean]] (Republican), incumbent Senator\n*John S. Martin (Socialist)\n*[[A. Harry Moore]] (Democrat), Governor of New Jersey\n\n==General election==\n===Results===\n{{Election box begin no change|title=1934 United States Senate election in New Jersey<ref>{{cite web|url=http://clerk.house.gov/member_info/electionInfo/1934election.pdf|title=Statistics of the Congressional Election of November 3, 1934|publisher=Clerk of the United States House of Representatives|accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref><ref>https://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=267931</ref>}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n | party      = Democratic Party (US)\n | candidate  = [[A. Harry Moore]]\n | votes      = 785,971\n | percentage = 57.90%\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n | party      = Republican Party (US)\n | candidate  = [[Hamilton Fish Kean]] (Incumbent)\n | votes      = 554,483\n | percentage = 40.85%\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n | party      = Socialist Party (US)\n | candidate  = John S. Martin\n | votes      = 9,721\n | percentage = 0.72%\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n | party      = Communist Party (US)\n | candidate  = Rebecca Grecht\n | votes      = 2,874\n | percentage = 0.21%\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n | party      = Prohibition Party (US)\n | candidate  = Elwood Hollingshead\n | votes      = 2,072\n | percentage = 0.15%\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n | party      = Socialist Labor Party (US)\n | candidate  = John C. Butterworth\n | votes      = 1,640\n | percentage = 0.12%\n}}\n{{Election box candidate no change\n | party      = Independent Veteran\n | candidate  = William L. Detmering\n | votes      = 648\n | percentage = 0.05%\n}}\n{{Election box majority no change\n | votes      = 231,488\n | percentage = 17.05%\n}}\n{{Election box turnout no change\n | votes      = 1,357,409\n | percentage =\n}}\n{{Election box gain with party link no change\n | winner     = Democratic Party (US)\n | loser      = Republican Party (US)\n | swing      =\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n== See also ==\n*[[1934 United States Senate elections]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n[[Category:1934 United States Senate elections|New Jersey]]\n[[Category:United States Senate elections in New Jersey|1934]]\n[[Category:1934 New Jersey elections]]\n<br />{{New Jersey-election-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Election\n| election_name = 1934 United States Senate election in New Jersey\n| country = New Jersey\n| flag_year = 1908\n| type = presidential\n| ongoing = no\n| previous_election = 1928 United States Senate election in New Jersey\n| previous_year = 1928\n| next_election = 1938 United States Senate special election in New Jersey\n| next_year = 1938 (special)\n| election_date = November 6, 1934\n| image1 = [[File:Arthur Harry Moore circa 1926.png|x150px]]\n| nominee1 = '''[[A. Harry Moore]]'''\n| party1 = Democratic Party (United States)\n| popular_vote1 = '''785,971'''\n| percentage1 = '''57.90%'''\n| image2 = [[File:Hamiltonkean.jpg|x150px]]\n| nominee2 = [[Hamilton F. Kean]]\n| party2 = Republican Party (United States)\n| popular_vote2 = 554,483\n| percentage2 = 40.85%\n| title = Senator\n| before_election = [[Hamilton F. Kean]]\n| before_party = Republican Party (United States)\n| after_election = [[A. Harry Moore]]\n| after_party = Democratic Party (United States)\n}}\n{{ElectionsNJ}}\nThe '''United States Senate election of 1934 in New Jersey''' was held on November 6, 1934. \n\nIncumbent [[Republican Party (US)|Republican]] Senator [[Hamilton F. Kean]] ran for re-election to a second term in office, but was defeated by Governor of New Jersey [[A. Harry Moore]] in a landslide. \n\nThis was among the nine seats Democrats gained in this year's elections. \n\n==Candidates==\n*John C. Butterworth (Socialist Labor)\n*William L. Detmering (Independent Voters)\n*Rebecca Grecht (Communist)\n*Elwood Hollingsworth (Prohibition)\n*[[Hamilton F. Kean]] (Republican), incumbent Senator\n*John S. Martin (Socialist)\n*[[A. Harry Moore]] (Democrat), Governor of New Jersey\n\n==General election==\n===Results===\n{{Elect